\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\fs28\lang1033\f4\fs28\f4\lang1025\qj 40.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s3\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs28\lang1033\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033\i0\b0 The respondent argues that the Commission would also have to allege that the imposition of this allegedly unrelated condition is anti-competitive in its effect.  However, we reject this argument.  The acts described in 8(d)(i)-(v) are characterised in Sect
ion 8(d) as \'91the following exclusionary acts\'92 which in turn are defined as \'91act(s) that impede(s) or prevent(s) a firm entering into, or expanding within, a market\'92.  Thus these acts, in contrast with the general category of \'91exclusionary acts\'92 referred to
 in Section 8(c), are presumptively anti-competitive \'96 a complainant is not required to allege or prove facts to this effect.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s3\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs28\lang1033\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\fs28\lang1033\f4\fs28\f4\lang1025\qj 41.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s3\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs28\lang1033\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033\i0\b0 In other words the acts described in Section 8(d)(1)-(v) are {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i per se} anti-competitive.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s13\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch{\*\cs21\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up8\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f5\fs20\lang2057\i0\b0 For a further elaboration of the nature of section 8(d) practices see {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\b\loch\b The Competition Commission v Patensie Sitrus Beherend Beperk and Jakobus Johannes Petrus Bezuidenhout v Patensie Sitrus Beherend Beperk} (case number 37/CR/Jun01)}}}
{\*\cs21\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up12\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f1\fs24\lang7177\loch\f1\fs24\lang7177 }  However, in contrast with the acts described in Section 4(1)(b)(i)-(iii) and those described in Sections 8(a) and (b) they are not {\rtlch\ai\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i per se} contraventions of the Act.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s13\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f5\fs20\lang2057\loch\f5\fs20\lang2057{\*\cs21\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up8\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f5\fs20\lang2057\i0\b0 For a further elaboration of section 4(1)(b) complaints see {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\b\loch\b American Natural Soda Ash Corporation and Others v Botswana Ash (Pty) Limited and Others} (case number 49/CR/A/Jul00).}}}
{\*\cs21\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up12\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f1\fs24\lang7177\loch\f1\fs24\lang7177 }  T
his is because Section 8(d) offences permit of a pro-competitive defence, a showing that the {\rtlch\ai\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i presumed }anti-competitive consequences of a Section 8(d) Act are outweighed by the \'91technological, efficiency or other pro-competitive gains\'92.  Section 4(1)(b) off
ences (as well as Section 8(a) and (b) offences), on the other hand, admit of no such defence.  }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s3\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs28\lang1033\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\fs28\lang1033\f4\fs28\f4\lang1025\qj 42.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s3\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs28\lang1033\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033\i0\b0 The respondent makes much of the potential balancing of anti- and pro-competitive consequences \'96  \'91if my opponent is not required to establish the precise anti-competitive consequences of a section 8(d) act, how\'92 the respondent effectively asks, \'91will I es
tablish that its pro-competitive gains outweigh those effects\'92? This difficulty, even if it were to be admitted, cannot change the clear statement in Section 8(d) that provides that all of these acts are defined as exclusionary and hence anti-competitive. 
 It may well be that, for the purposes of balancing the pro- and anti-competitive consequences, one may have to delve more deeply into the {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i extent} of the anti-competitive consequences.  However one does not have to do any further delving in order to establi
sh the {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i existence }of anti-competitive effects, to establish whether or not a practice described in Section 8(d) is indeed anti-competitive \'96 this the Act establishes for us.  }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s3\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs28\lang1033\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\fs28\lang1033\f4\fs28\f4\lang1025\qj 43.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s3\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs28\lang1033\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033\i0\b0 It is, in any event, our view that the balancing is a less precise enquiry than that suggested by the respondent \'96 it is, inevitably, a qualitative rather than quantitative balance that is sought.  Hence, by way of example, if the firm imposing an alleged 
tie was, in addition to being dominant in terms of the Act, actually a monopoly supplier then we would inevitably conclude that it would have to show massive pro-competitive gains in order to outweigh the effect of its monopoly status \'96 a would be purchase
r of product produced by the dominant firm would have literally no choice but to use the monopolist\'92s product and thus accept any condition imposed in a contract of sale. If, on the other hand, the firm, despite its formally dominant status, nevertheless f
aced significant competition, we might well conclude when doing the balancing that the anti-competitive consequences were relatively minor and the pro-competitive showing required, concomitantly less onerous.   But, we repeat, it is not necessary to establ
ish that the act is indeed exclusionary or anti-competitive \'96 it is sufficient to establish that the respondent is dominant and that it perpetrated the act alleged.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s3\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs28\lang1033\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\fs28\lang1033\f4\fs28\f4\lang1025\qj 44.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s3\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs28\lang1033\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033\i0\b0 We do however acknowledge that the second leg of Section 8(d)(iii) \'96 the imposition of an unrelated condition on the sale of a product \'96 is, on the face of it, peculiarly at odds with the other practices listed in Section 8(d)(i)-(v).   Each of the other a
cts listed here are well-established anti-competitive acts. This is the reason why the Act distinguishes these acts from the general category of exclusive acts referred to in Section 8(c) and why, in particular, it does not require a showing of anti-compet
itive effect in relation to the acts described in Section 8(d).  However while \'91tying\'92 \'96 the practice of conditionally linking the purchase of a desired product to the purchase of an unrelated product, which is the act clearly described in the first leg of
 Section 8(d)(iii) \'96 easily falls into this category of what the US courts have referred to as \'91black letter\'92 anti-competitive acts, the same could not be said of the imposition of an unrelated {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i condition}. It is quite conceivable that a condition, possibly 
even one that is onerous or \'91unfair\'92, may nevertheless have no impact upon competition whatsoever.  On this literal reading of the Act, the respondent may well be justified in insisting that when dealing with the practice of imposing an unrelated condition
 there should be a showing of an anti-competitive effect.  On the face of it, the imposition of an unrelated condition indeed bears little similarity to a tying arrangement, the essential feature of which is the linking of two unrelated {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i markets}. It would a
ppear then that this single practice is at odds with the other acts listed in Section 8(d) including the act of tying described in the first part of Section 8(d)(iii). }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s3\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs28\lang1033\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\fs28\lang1033\f4\fs28\f4\lang1025\qj 45.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s3\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs28\lang1033\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033\i0\b0 However, in our view this anomaly is eliminated by a purposive reading of the Act.  The clear purpose of this section is to describe a number of well-documented anti-competitive acts and to declare them {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i per se} anti-competitive.  The drafters would have not
 intended to extend this category to cover a practice which, on its face, may have little to do with competition and which the case law has certainly not identified as a significant anti-competitive practice.  }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s3\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs28\lang1033\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\fs28\lang1033\f4\fs28\f4\lang1025\qj 46.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s3\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs28\lang1033\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033\i0\b0 There is, however, a relatively straightforward explanation of this apparent anomaly.  The first act described in section 8(d)(iii) is a classic tying arrangement \'96 it is described as such in a number of authoritative US and EU judgments and in scholarly c
ommentary.  The essential features of a tying arrangement are the existence of two distinct products, that is, two distinct markets. In one of these markets, the \'91tying market\'92 or \'91tying product\'92, the alleged transgressor is dominant.  It seeks to leverage
 advantage for itself or for an ally in the second market by requiring a would-be purchaser in the market in which it is dominant to favour itself or its ally in the second or tied market.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s13\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch{\*\cs21\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up8\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f5\fs20\lang2057\i0\b0 According to Areeda ({\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\b\loch\b Antitrust Law} at 1700d) in the US {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i \'93The original, continuing, and most fundamental concern about tying is \'91leverage\'92\'94}. He quotes the US Supreme Court\'92s definition of leverage where it held that {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i \'93\'92Leverage\'92 is loosely defined \'85 as a sup
plier\'92s power to induce his customer for one product to buy a second product from him that would not otherwise be purchased solely on the merit of that second product.\'94} {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\b\loch\b [Jefferson Parish Hosp. Dist. No 2 v Hyde, 466 U.S. 2 14 n.20 (1984)]}. In {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\b\loch\b \'93The Economic
s of EC Competition Law\'94 at paragraph 5.13}, Walker and Bishop state: {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i \'93What may be referred to as the \'91intuitive\'92 antitrust concern with tying is that a firm that is a monopolist in one market might be able to \'91leverage\'92 this monopoly into another market an
d thus raise prices above the competitive level in this second market. The concern is that the monopolist uses his market power in the tying good market in order to improve anti-competitively his position in the tied good market.\'94 }{\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\b\loch\i\b  }{\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\b\loch\b In Tetra Pak v Commissio
n [1994] ECR II \'96755} the European Court of First Instance found that contractual clauses whereby Tetra Pak tied the sale of its carton packaging materials to the sale of its filling machines by requiring that purchasers of the filling machines use only the
ir only their cartons infringed the provisions of article 82(d) (article 86(d) at the time). This was because these clauses eliminated competition at the level of carton sales by tying making this market to the market for filling machines where Tetra Pak w
as dominant.}}}
{\*\cs21\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up12\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f1\fs24\lang7177\loch\f1\fs24\lang7177 }  The element of leveraging is an essential feature of tying.  Thes
e elements are clearly described in the first leg of 8(d)(iii) \'96 \'91selling goods or services on condition that the buyer purchases separate goods or services unrelated to the object of a contract\'92.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s3\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs28\lang1033\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\fs28\lang1033\f4\fs28\f4\lang1025\qj 47.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s3\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs28\lang1033\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033\i0\b0 What then, are we expected to make of the second leg of section 8(d)(iii) - the imposition of an unrelated condition? This, on the face it, does not appear to require the existence of two markets or products.  In the present case the condition is that Pape
rcor, the would-be purchaser of the allegedly dominant firm\'92s product, pay legal costs sustained by the respondent \'96 in this instance it is clear that two products or markets are not linked by the tie, there is no leveraging of market power. In our view th
e inclusion of a prohibition on the imposition of \'91unrelated conditions\'92 simply reflects the cautious approach of the legislature, a caution appropriate in a field of law that potential transgressors have both the incentive and resources to evade.  It is c
onceivable that a dominant firm may seek to impose a tie, may, in other works, seek to leverage its power into a second market, without explicitly specifying that the intended victim of the abuse purchase product in the second market.  It may achieve this 
by imposing a condition in the sale agreement \'96 for example, a technical standard or specification required when purchasing spare parts or some or other complementary input - that would lead its customer directly to the door of the intended beneficiary in 
the second market.  Because the condition specified a standard rather than \'91separate goods or services\'92 the perpetrator of the tie may escape scrutiny under Section 8(d)(iii).  It is this potential loophole that the second leg of Section 8(d)(iii) is inten
ded to close.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s3\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs28\lang1033\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\fs28\lang1033\f4\fs28\f4\lang1025\qj 48.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s3\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs28\lang1033\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033\i0\b0 The fact that the two legs are located in the same sub-paragraph suggests that they are both intended to address the same anti-competitive ill, namely tying. If they were not conceptually linked and the second link refers to some conduct that is distinct f
rom tying, it would presumably have been set out in its own self-standing sub-paragraph. The architecture of paragraph (d), which sets out a different species of exclusionary act in each of its sub-paragraphs, tends to support this conclusion.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s3\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs28\lang1033\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\fs28\lang1033\f4\fs28\f4\lang1025\qj 49.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s3\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs28\lang1033\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033\i0\b0 Our view is supported by the observation that Article 82(d) of the EU Treaty specifies as an abuse of dominance {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i \'93making the conclusions of contracts subject to acceptance by other parties of supplementary obligations which, by their nature or according to 
commercial usage, have no connection with the subject of such contracts.\'94} It is instructive that there is no single EU case in which the offending unconnected \'91supplementary obligations\'92 has not linked separate markets or products.  And there are authorita
tive EU decisions in which this Article has been used to impeach conditions that have tied two markets, in which, in other words, a dominant firm has sought to leverage its market power into an unrelated market.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s13{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch{\*\cs21\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up8\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f5\fs20\lang2057\i0\b0 See footnote 15 {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i supra}.}}}
{\*\cs21\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up12\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f1\fs24\lang7177\loch\f1\fs24\lang7177 }}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s3\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs28\lang1033\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\fs28\lang1033\f4\fs28\f4\lang1025\qj 50.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s3\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs28\lang1033\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033\i0\b0 Accordingly because the Commission has failed to disclose facts that will, if later proven, establish that the unrelated condition in question will link two markets \'96 in our view, an essential element for a successful prosecution under Section 8(d)(iii) \'96 
we conclude that no cause of action has been disclosed and the exception is upheld.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s3\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs28\lang1033\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\fs28\lang1033\f4\fs28\f4\lang1025\qj 51.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s3\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs28\lang1033\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033\i0\b0 We note that even if we have erred in our interpretation of the \'91unrelated condition\'92 component of Section 8(d)(iii) we would have still upheld the exception.  This is because, as clarified earlier, the Commission has failed to disclose the facts upon whic
h it shall rely in order to prove that the condition in question \'96 the payment of the legal costs \'96 is indeed unrelated to the object of the contract of sale.  As we have noted, on the face of it, the condition and the object of the contract that the parti
es seek to conclude are intimately related and there are no facts disclosed that allege the contrary.  Accordingly, even on this interpretation no cause of action is disclosed and the exception is upheld.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s3\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs28\lang1033\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\fs28\lang1033\f4\fs28\f4\lang1025\qj 52.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s3\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs28\lang1033\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs28\lang1033\i0\b0 Note that we are not arguing that the imposition of a truly unrelated condition can never be anti-competitive.  For example, a refusal to deal, a possible anti-competitive act although one clearly distinguished from tying, may conceivably be affected by im
position of a manifestly unacceptable unrelated condition on a sale \'96 in other words an unrelated and unacceptable condition may be imposed as a device to force a would-be purchaser to walk away from a contract of sale. However, a refusal to deal would in 
all likelihood be prosecuted under Section 8(c) unless it met the onerous and unusual requirements contained in Section 8(d)(ii).  The distinction between a Section 8(c) and a Section 8(d) prosecution is by no means academic.  As already noted, because Sec
tion 8(d) describes acts whose anti-competitive consequences have been established by a century of anti-trust jurisprudence, a successful prosecution does not have to establish the anti-competitive or exclusionary consequences of the act in question \'96 they
 are presumed to be present.  However, for a prosecution in terms of Section 8(c) to succeed it is necessary to establish that the act complained of is indeed exclusionary, that it \'91impedes or prevents a firm entering into, or expanding within a market\'92.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s13\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch{\*\cs21\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up8\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f5\fs20\lang2057\i0\b0 The imperative to establish the anti-competitive consequences of a \'91refusal to deal\'92 are, arguably, particularly clear insofar as forced dealing disturbs a broad principle of anti-trust, viz, that \'91absent a purpose of creating or maintaining a monopoly me
rchants should be free to trade with whomever they choose and on such conditions as they choose\'92  (Glen O. Robinson \'91{\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\b\loch\b On Refusing to Deal with Rivals\'92}{\ul\ulc0  }University of Virginia School of Law, Law and Economics Research Paper Series, Working Paper No 01-3, May 
2001).  This principle is confirmed time and again by the courts with possibly its best-known formulation in {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\b\loch\b United States v. Colgate and Co 250 U.S. 300 (1919)}}}}
